<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRESERVING A GOURMET TRADITION; 
</P>
<P>
3 GENERATIONS OF WARDS GROW AND CAN FRUITS AND CONDIMENTS IN SIERRA MADRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BERKLEY HUDSON, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
E. Waldo Ward &amp; Son is an unexpected world of gourmet smells. Cloves, 
cinnamon and ginger scents rose from an antiquated electric grinder where 
Jeffrey Ward, 24, worked on a recent morning in Sierra Madre. In two 
stainless-steel kettles, sliced circles of onions topped a steaming meat sauce 
made from a family recipe. 
</P>
<P>
Next to another 100-gallon kettle, Jeffrey's father, Richard, 55, stirred a 
long spatula in a stewing batch of Oregon red raspberries. 
</P>
<P>
Two women spooned nine-ounce portions of mango chutney, taken from barrels 
shipped from Bombay, India, into jars. A vinegary smell wafted from tubs of 
green olives, imported from Spain. 
</P>
<P>
Among the large lots and big houses on East Highland Avenue in this small town 
hard against the San Gabriel foothills, Waldo Ward &amp; Son, in a rambling 
warehouse beside a Victorian house and a red barn, is hardly noticeable. 
</P>
<P>
For 99 years, the Wards have been canning and preserving oranges, kumquats and 
other fruits and condiments. Much of the produce is grown on Ward land in the 
San Gabriel Valley. 
</P>
<P>
Today, three generations of Ward men operate the business from the three-acre 
plot where the homestead and barn were built in 1903. The recipes are 
time-tested, many of them gathered by the founder, the late E. Waldo Ward Sr., 
who took lengthy trips selling gourmet food around the West in the early part 
of this century. 
</P>
<P>
"We don't give a damn about volume," said Jeffrey's grandfather, 87-year-old E. 
Waldo Ward Jr. "We give a damn about quality product." 
</P>
<P>
Jeffrey said: "We have a niche, selling to people who want better quality. 
That's where we come in, like a Rolls-Royce." 
</P>
<P>
Waldo, Richard and Jeffrey: Each proudly speaks of following in his father's 
footsteps and of being firmly planted in Sierra Madre. The three bachelors 
(Waldo's wife died in 1971, and Richard was divorced 10 years ago) live 
together in the Victorian house. 
</P>
<P>
"There isn't another place like it in Sierra Madre where you have the same 
family living on a place for four generations," Richard said. 
</P>
<P>
Ask Waldo, a Pomona College chemistry major in the 1920s, why he never left 
Sierra Madre, and he will look at you as if you're crazy to suggest he might 
have. 
</P>
<P>
Ask Richard, who graduated from UC Davis with a degree in agricultural 
economics in 1957, and he acknowledges that he wasn't sure that he would uphold 
tradition. In fact, he worked six years for Del Monte Foods Inc. in the Bay 
Area. But he said he found that "when you work for a large company, you just 
feel like you're a smaller cog in the works." 
</P>
<P>
Ask Jeffrey, Richard's only son (his two daughters aren't affiliated with the 
business), and he says he wanted to work in the family firm since he was 12. He 
majored in food science and technology at UC Davis. 
</P>
<P>
In an office cluttered with everything from the mounted skin of a diamondback 
rattlesnake killed in the groves to black-and-white photographs of himself as a 
boy, Waldo Jr. held forth on his marmalade birthright. 
</P>
<P>
Waldo Sr., he said, developed tuberculosis when he worked for a New York fancy 
foods company and in 1887 headed west for drier air. He eventually settled in 
Sierra Madre, then a mecca for tuberculosis patients. 
</P>
<P>
He bought 10 acres for a house and orange groves, developed his own thriving 
marmalade line and shipped oranges back East by the crate. He even imported to 
Sierra Madre two trees from Seville, Spain, known for its tart oranges. 
</P>
<P>
Ward obtained many recipes when, as a traveling salesman, he met women recently 
arrived from Great Britain, where they had worked in preserves factories. Now 
typed on 3-by-5 cards, the recipes still are used in the business, which 
employs two dozen workers during peak periods. 
</P>
<P>
As business expanded and railway companies, for example, bought his 
British-style marmalade, he acquired more land. Ward's preserves graced 
breakfast tables in Southern Pacific and Santa Fe dining cars and in railroad 
hotels at depots across the West. 
</P>
<P>
Over the years, the Wards have sold groves to be subdivided, but they say they 
have no plans to sell out. Waldo Ward pointed to a computer and a fax machine 
-- recent additions, thanks to his grandson, who wants to expand their 
mail-order business. Just last year, the firm began accepting credit cards. 
</P>
<P>
Ward has filled orders for many California establishments, including Knott's 
Berry Farm, Jurgensen's Groceries and Pea Soup Andersen's Restaurants. "In the 
'20s," he said, "we used to sell to all the good stores in Boston and New York 
City." 
</P>
<P>
Outside, Richard Ward surveyed the palms, the fruit-heavy orange trees and the 
San Gabriel foothills to the north. He passed under a tin-roofed shed where the 
morning sun cured walnuts. As he headed in to finish a batch of red raspberry 
preserves, he said: "You get spoiled living here." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Richard Ward carries on a 99-year family tradition of canning as he puts 
covers on cans after pouring in blackberry preserves. ; Photo, Jeffery Ward 
walks by the old red barn in back of his home. The barn was built in 1903 by 
company founder E. Waldo Ward Sr. ; Photo, E. Waldo Ward Jr. shows off some of 
the family's gourmet products and gift items that are manufactured at the 
Sierra Madre homestead. LOU MACK / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
