<HEADLINE>
<P>
ISRAEL HIGH COURT QUASHES EMERGENCY HOUSING PLANS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
JERUSALEM 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Israeli Supreme Court today quashed the emergency powers granted to Housing 
Minister Ariel Sharon for a crash building program to house a wave of Soviet 
Jewish immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
Israel's new right-wing government gave Sharon the right July 1 to circumvent 
existing rules in order to rush construction of 3,000 new apartments and 
prepare the groundwork for another 8,000. 
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court ruled in favor of parliamentarian Avraham Poraz of the 
centrist Shinui party, who charged that Sharon's emergency powers were 
unreasonable and illegal. 
</P>
<P>
"It was possible to build houses at all the sites that Minister Sharon wanted 
to build according to the existing law," Poraz told Army radio after the 
ruling. 
</P>
<P>
"In fact these emergency measures were intended to create an atmosphere of 
public hysteria, an atmosphere of distress." 
</P>
<P>
Sharon, a hard-liner who orchestrated Israel's 1982 invasion of Lebanon, 
received broad powers in the new government to handle the immigration of 
hundreds of thousands of Soviet Jews. 
</P>
<P>
In a second blow to Sharon's ambitious plans to cope with Soviet immigration, 
Tourism Minister Gideon Patt attacked his emergency plan announced Sunday to 
house immigrants in hotels. 
</P>
<P>
"Three-, four- and five-star hotels will not become absorption centers," Patt 
told reporters. "I won't allow it." 
</P>
<P>
Pressure on the government to solve the housing crisis grows daily as the 
number of homeless Israelis swells and dozens of tent cities spring up across 
the country. 
</P>
<P>
The growing demand for space has forced up rents, driving many young couples 
and poor families out of their apartments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
